gh volumes of requests prevent the redirect from executing, causing POST data to accumulate in the session and consume memory. The knowledge file covers this risk and suggests using business action redirects as a mitigation, though it omits the initial mechanism description of how POST data is normally stored and cleared. I've identified the key issue: the knowledge file omits the mechanism explanation for how the DoS vulnerability works—specifically, that POST data gets stored in the session during redirect and then cleared afterward. This context helps explain why the vulnerability exists, though it's more background information than critical implementation guidance, so I'm marking it as a minor omission.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16950,"cache_read_input_tokens":35069,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":16950,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a1880dc4-4980-4074-a51a-e0a0c1eb00e5","uuid":"400b1892-76ec-4f44-9a66-32dcd84b7386"}
